========================================
CONSISTENT HASHING – QUICK NOTES
========================================

🔹 What is Consistent Hashing?
- Distributed hashing technique used in scalable systems
- Maps BOTH:
  → Nodes (servers)
  → Keys (data)
  onto a virtual ring (hash ring)

Goal:
- Minimize data movement when nodes are added/removed

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Why not simple hashing?

Normal approach:
  index = hash(key) % N

Problem:
- If N changes (add/remove server)
  → Almost ALL keys get remapped
  → Cache/database becomes useless

Example:
- 100 servers → add 101st server
→ ~99% keys move ❌

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Core Idea (Hash Ring)

- Hash space forms a circle (0 → MAX)
- Nodes are placed on the ring using hash(node)
- Keys are placed using hash(key)
- Key goes to FIRST node clockwise

Rule:
  key → next node on the ring (clockwise)

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 How it works (step-by-step)

1) Hash all servers → place on ring
2) Hash key → locate position on ring
3) Move clockwise
4) First server encountered stores the key

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 What happens when nodes change?

✔ Node added:
- Only keys in its range shift to new node

✔ Node removed:
- Only its keys move to next node

Impact:
- Only ~1/N keys get redistributed
- NOT entire dataset

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Virtual Nodes (VNodes)

Problem:
- Uneven distribution of keys

Solution:
- Each physical server = multiple virtual nodes

Benefits:
- Better load balancing
- Avoid hotspots
- More uniform key distribution

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Why it is used

Used in:
- Distributed caches (Redis, Memcached)
- NoSQL databases (Cassandra, Dynamo-style systems)
- Load balancers
- CDNs

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Advantages

+ Minimal data movement on scaling
+ Highly scalable
+ Fault tolerant
+ Works well in dynamic clusters

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Disadvantages

- More complex than modulo hashing
- Requires ring management
- Uneven load possible without virtual nodes
- Hot keys still possible

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Complexity

- Lookup: O(log N) (or O(1) with optimizations)
- Rebalancing: only partial key movement (~1/N)

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Key Interview Points

- Fixes drawback of hash(key) % N
- Uses circular hash space (ring)
- Key → nearest clockwise node
- Virtual nodes improve balance
- Core concept in distributed systems

--------------------------------------------------

🧠 One-liner:
Consistent hashing is a technique that maps keys and nodes onto a hash ring so that only a minimal number of keys move when nodes are added or removed.